b'' b'' b'the recent rise of nostalgia in this group, combined with the' b'incredible level of utter bullshit, has prompted me to comb' b'through my archives and pull out some of "the best of alt.atheism"' b"for your reading pleasure. i'll post a couple of these a day" b'unless group concensus demands that i stop, or i run out of good' b'material.' b'' b"i haven't been particularly careful in the past about saving" b'attributions. i think the following comes from john a. johnson,' b"but someone correct me if i'm wrong. this is probably the longest" b'of my entire collection.' b'' b'________________________________________________________' b'' b'' b'so that the' b'prophecy be' b'fulfilled' b'' b'* b'' b'in considering the christian religion, and judging it' b'according to its claims, it is important to look at its claims at' b'fulfilling earlier jewish prophecy. the scribe matthew is perhaps' b'the most eager to draw out what he thinks are prophetic answers in' b"the career of jesus of nazareth. as you will see, matthew's main" b'strategy is to take various old testament passages, often not even' b'about the promised messiah, and apply them to the circumstances in' b'the new testament. we must also bear in mind the question of the' b'authenticity of the accounts. since the gospels were written at' b'least years after jesus was executed, we do not know how much' b'happened exactly as stated. but, for purposes of analysis, we' b'will take particular claims at face value.' b'' b'immanuel:' b'' b'we begin, of course, at the beginning.' b'' b'(mt "[mary] will bear a son, and you,' b"joseph, will name him 'jesus' (which means g'd is" b'salvation), for he will save his people from their' b'sins." all this happened to fulfil what the lord had' b'spoken by a prophet:' b'' b'[isaiah in the days of ahaz (c. bce),' b'king of judah, rezin of syria and pekah of israel made' b'war on jerusalem (capitol of judah), but could not' b'quite conquer it. when the house of david (i.e. ahaz