excursion to egypt, as if he' b'wishes to liken jesus to moses. this was done to escape an' b'alleged infanticidal rampage of the king, herod.' b'' b'[mt ...and remained there until the death of' b'herod. this was to fulfil what the lord had spoken:' b'"out of egypt i have cal-led my son."' b'' b'' b'what the lord really said was this.' b'' b'[hosea when israel was a child, i loved him.' b'and, out of egypt i called my son. the more i called' b'them (my people), the more they went from me; they' b"kept sacrificing to the ba'als, and kept burning" b'incense to idols.' b'' b"matthew conveniently omits the rest of hosea's oracle. but, it" b'was indeed israel that, once called out of egypt, wanted to' b'return. this is history. jesus is certainly not being spoken of' b'here. and, if we are to draw some kind of parallel here, we wind' b"up with a jesus that flees and resists g'd. again, this prophecy" b'is just not as convincing as matthew probably had hoped.' b'' b'rachel weeps:' b'' b'while jesus is off vacationing in egypt, matthew says that' b'king herod sought to kill him, and thus ordered the executions of' b'all young male children. matthew then writes,' b'' b'[mt by this, that which was spoken by the' b'prophet jeremiah was fulfilled:' b'' b'"a voice was heard in ramah, wailing and loud' b'lamentation-- rachel weeping for her children;' b'she refused to be consoled, because they were' b'no more."' b'' b'the reference is to a passage in jeremiah referring to the' b'carrying off of israel into exile by sargon (of assyria) in b'bce. rachel, the ancestor of the major tribes of israel, ephraim,' b'and manasseh, is said to weep for her descendants who are "no' b'more." it is metaphorical, of course, since rachel lived and dies' b'before the hebrews were even in the egyptian exile.' b'it is interesting to note that it was leah, not rachel, who' b'was the ancestor of the judeans (the land where jesus and' b'bethlehem were). if anyone should do weeping for her "children,"' b'it is leah. the only connexion that rachel has with bethlehem is' b'that the legends have it that she was buried north of the city,' b'"on the way to ephrath, (bethlehem)."' b'as for herod and his infanticide, it is rather unlikely' b'that such an event actually occurred. one never knows, but the' b'event is not mentioned or alluded to anywhere else in the bible,' b'nor is it mentioned in any of the secular records of the time.' b'herod was particularly unliked in his reign, and many far less' b'evil deeds of herod were carefully recorded. this might be a' b"prime example of how events were added to jesus's life to enhance" b"the message of the church's gospel." b"because of the whole story's similarity to the tale of the" b'infant moses in egypt, it is highly likely that it is a device set' b'up by matthew to add prophetic, yet artificial, approval of jesus.' b'it is not surprising that matthew conveniently neglects to mention' b'the rest of the jeremiah quote. the "children" the prophet' b"speaks of are not dead, but exiled in the assyrian empire. g'd" b'comforts the weeping rachel, saying that the children will be' b'returned-- he will gather them back together. of course, this' b"would not suit matthew's purpose, as the children he speaks of are" b'dead for good. again, the "prophecy" matthew sets up is not even' b'that, and to anyone who bothers to check it out, is not too' b'convincing.' b'' b'the nazarene:' b'' b'we do not even have to go to the next chapter to find' b'another matthean prophecy. after leaving egypt, joseph wife' b'take the infant jesus to live in the city of nazareth,' b'' b'[mt ...that what was spoken of by the prophets' b'might be fulfilled, "he shall be called a nazarene."' b'' b'first thing we notice is that matthew does not mention the name of' b'the prophet(s) this time. second, we have to ask who "he" is.' b'there are no messianic prophecies speaking of a nazarene. worse,' b'there are no prophecies, period, mentioning a nazarene. still' b'worse, there are no nazarenes mentioned in the old testament at' b"all. in the book of judges, an angel tells samson's mother that" b'she will,' b'' b'[judges "...conceive and bear a son. no razor' b'shall tough his head, for he will be a nazirite to his' b'god from the day of his birth. he will deliver israel' b'from the hands of the philistines."' b'' b"this is of course not a prophecy of jesus, or the messiah of g'd." b'but, it is the best that can be found. obviously, matthew has' b'begun to go overboard in cut-and-paste prophecies, in that he is' b'simple making them up now.' b'' b'bearing our' b'diseases:' b'' b'jesus next goes around healing people of physical illnesses' b'and disabilities.' b'' b'[mt this was to fulfil what was spoken by the' b'prophet isaiah, "he took our infirmities and bore our' b'diseases."' b'' b'as expected, the verse quoted in isaiah is quoted out of context,' b'and a few words are skewed to fit the christian scheme. we have,' b'' b'[is surely he, [the suffering servant], has' b'borne our sickness, and carried our pains.' b'' b'from a reading of the surrounding passages in isaiah, we know that' b'the prophet is speaking in present tense of the collective nation' b"of israel, jehovah's chosen servant and people. he speaks to the" b'israelites suffering in exile, in the voice of the gentile nations' b'that look upon it. this image is deeply ingrained in jewish' b'identity --an image of a chastised, yet cherished, israel as the' b"instrument of the nations' salvation by g'd." b'the verses speak of israel taking on the sicknesses which' b'are the literal and metaphorical manifestations of guilt and' b'discipline. they do not speak of a "servant" going around and' b'healing people. notice that the servant in isaiah takes on the' b'sicknesses and pains of the nations (and individual jews). jesus,' b'as we all know, did not take the diseases onto himself. the' b'verses here in isaiah are not a prophecy of something to come, but' b'rather something that had already happened. while it is believed' b'that jesus took on the eternal punishment of hell, he did not bear' b'the illnesses he healed. so, while someone might want to say' b'that, figuratively, jesus reenacted the deeds of israel in his' b"spiritual atonement, he has to admit that matthew's parallel" b'misses where he intended it to have its effect.' b'' b'' b'silent messiah:' b'' b'upon healing multitudes of commoners, it is said that jesus' b"ordered them to keep quiet, presumable so that he wouldn't arouse" b'the attention of the local rulers.' b'' b'[mt this was to fulfill what was spoken by' b'the prophet isaiah.' b'' b'"behold my servant whom i have chosen, my beloved,' b'with whom my soul is pleased. i will put my spirit on' b'him, and he will announce justice to the gentiles. he' b'will not wrangle or cry aloud, nor will anyone hear' b'his voice in the streets. he will not break a bruised' b'reed or quench a smoldering wick until he brings' b'justice to victory, and the gentiles will hope in his' b'name."' b'' b'the isaiah passage quoted reads,' b'' b'[is behold my servant whom i uphold, my' b'chosen, in whom my soul delights. i have put my' b'spirit on him, and he will bring forth justice to the' b'nations. we will not cry or lift up his voice, or' b'make it heard in the street. he will not break a' b'bruised reed, or quench a smoldering wick. he will' b'faithfully bring forth justice. he will not fail' b'(burn dimly) or be discouraged (bruised) until he has' b'established justice in the earth. and the coastlands' b'await his law.' b'' b'you see, matthew has conveniently left out part of the passage,' b'because it does not suit the dealings of jesus. christians could' b'never think of jesus failing, never would the "light" of mankind' b'burn dimly. but, the servant nation of israel will indeed come to' b'an end when its job is done. when the gentiles come to embrace' b"g'd there will no longer be a chosen people, but rather all will" b"be the children of g'd. also, the ending phrase has been changed" b'from the judaic "...the coastlands await his law." to the' b'christologic, "the gentiles will hope in his name." while the' b'original proclaims the torah law of jehovah, the other rewrites it' b'to fit its strange doctrine of "believing in the name." if one' b'has any doubt the servant referred to is not jesus, one has only' b'to read the whole chapter, isaiah and hear about the beloved' b'but blind and imperfect servant, "a people robbed and' b'plundered..." so, we see that when matthew\'s attempt at' b'"prophecy" is examined, it crumbles.' b'' b'three days and' b'three nights:' b'' b'now we come upon a prophecy supposedly uttered by the very' b'mouth of the god jesus himself. he speaks of his crucifixion and' b'resurrection.' b'' b'[mt for as jonah was in the belly of the' b'whale for three days and three nights, so will the son' b'of man be in the heart of the earth three days and' b'three nights.' b'' b'before any further discussion can occur, it is necessary to know' b'how the jews understood days. as far as day names went, each was' b'24 hours long, lasting from sunset 6pm to the following sunset' b'6pm. what was referred to as a "day" was the period of light from' b'6am to the ending sunset at 6pm. thus, according to our time' b'scale, a sabbath day began at 6pm friday evening, and lasted until' b'6pm saturday evening. this is why the jews celebrate their' b'sabbath on the daylight portion of saturdays, instead of sundays.' b"(it seems like a real miracle that christians didn't forget that" b'saturday was indeed the seventh and last day of the week!) thus,' b'when days and nights are referred to together, hour daylight' b'portions and hour night periods are being spoken of. thus,' b'jesus says that he will be in the grave, or in hell, or otherwise' b'unresurrected for three days and three nights.' b'' b'as the good book tells us, jesus was crucified on the "ninth' b'hour," which is 3pm, friday afternoon. he then was put into the' b'grave sometime after that. then, jesus left the grave, "rose,"' b'before dawn of what we call sunday (the dawn after the sabbath was' b'over). what this means is that jesus was, using our time for' b'clarity, in the grave from 6pm friday night to some time before' b'6am sunday morning. we could also add a little time before 6pm' b'friday, since the bible is not specific here. what this means' b'using jewish time is that he was in the grave for one day, two' b'nights, and possibly a couple of hours of one day. certainly this' b'is a problem for jesus prediction. there is absolutely no way we' b'are even able to have his death involve three days and three' b'nights --even using modern time measurements. we then are led to' b"suspect that this error is another one of matthew's little" b'mistakes, and that the gospel writer put false words into his' b"god's mouth. and no matter who made the prediction, it is more" b'than unconvincing... it is counter-convincing.' b'' b'hearing b'understanding:' b'' b'jesus tool on a habit of speaking to his vast audiences in' b'parables-- stories in which a deeper meaning could be found, if' b'you were already one of the elect, those chosen to understand the' b'message of jesus. he reasons that those who can understand the' b'parables are the ones he wants. if the people cannot understand' b'them, there is no need to bother with them, since they will not' b'accept the "plain" message any better. matthew says,' b'' b'[mt with them [the audience] indeed in' b'fulfilled the prophecy of isaiah which says,' b'' b'"you will indeed hear but never understand; and you' b'will indeed see, but never perceive. because this' b"people's heart has grown dull, their ears are heavy of" b'hearing, and they have shut their eyes so the they' b'would not perceive with them, her with their ears, and' b'understand with their heart, and turn for me to heal' b'them."' b'' b'the original isaiah passages are part of his earlier works, his' b'call to the ministry. this is in bce, when israel is' b'flourishing, right before it falls under the authority of assyria.' b"isaiah sees the good times ending, and also a vision from g'd," b'calling him to bring reform to israel and judah.' b'' b'[is and g\'d said, "go, and say to this' b'people, `hear and hear, but do not understand; see and' b"see, but do not perceive.' make the heart of this" b'people fat, make their ears heavy, and shut their' b'eyes, so they will not see with their eyes, or hear' b'with their ears, and understand with their hearts, and' b'turn and be healed." then isaiah said, "how long,' b'lord?" and he said, "until the cities lie waste' b'without inhabitant, and houses without men, and the' b"land is utterly desolate, and the g'ds take men far" b'away, and forsaken places are many in the land. and' b'though a tenth will remain in it, it will be burned' b'again, like a terebinth or an oak whose stump still' b'stands when the tree is felled." the holy seed is its' b'stump.' b'' b"here we see that it is really g'd who causes the people of israel" b"to stop listening to the prophet's warnings, but reaffirms the" b"promise made to solomon's (and david's) seed/lineage. if you read" b'the rest of isaiah, you find that this is done to fulfil the plan' b"of g'd to use israel as a servant, a light to the nations. (look" b'at isaiah b'we see that matthew has cut-and-pasted just a little portion' b"of isaiah's verse, to suit his own gospel needs. more than that," b"he has altered the words, to make it fit the people who didn't" b"understand jesus's stories. and, as we see, isaiah's verses are" b"not prophecies, but rather commands from g'd to him, in the" b"present. once again, matthew's prophecy falls flat on its face." b'' b"matthew tries again to make jesus's parables look like they" b'have the prophetic approval.' b'' b'[mt ...he said nothing to them without a' b'parable. this was to fulfil what was spoken of by the' b'prop