oungsters calling jesus the messiah. but,' b'jesus replied as we might expect matthew to have done,' b'' b"[mt haven't you read? `out of the mouth of" b"babes and sucklings thou has brought perfect praise.'" b'' b'it is more likely that matthew made this response up since jesus' b'was never one to point out such little "prophetic" things and' b'since, as we might expect, the quote is in error, which seems to' b"fit matthew's track record quite well. we might ask jesus or" b'matthew, "haven\'t you read?" for the source reads,' b'' b'[psalms o yahweh our lord, how majestic is' b'your name in the whole world! you, whose glory is' b'chanted above the heavens by babes and infants, you' b'have founded a bulwark against your foes to still the' b'enemy and the avenger.' b'' b'the passages hardly need comment. there is no "perfect praise"' b"spoken of in the psalm, and what praise is there is given to g'd," b'not his messiah king, and not jesus. as mentioned, it seems to be' b"just one more case of matthew's pen making up convenient prophetic" b'scripture.' b'' b'yhvh said to' b'my lord...:' b'' b'jesus is said to have asked from whom the promised jewish' b'messiah-king is to be descended. the jews agree-- it is king' b'david. but, then jesus counters by quoting psalms b'' b'"the lord said to my lord, sit at my right hand, until' b'i put your enemies under your feet."' b'' b'taken at face value, jesus is denying the necessity of davidic' b'descent. one assumes he is in opposition to their answer. of' b'course, the christian answer is that he agrees, but is trying to' b'make some hidden point, to reveal some mystery about the divine' b"nature of the messiah-king. it's tempting to believe this, if one" b'is a christian and not interested in matters of investigation.' b'but, there are problems.' b"in jesus's time, the psalm was thought to be about the" b'messiah. and, it is easy to see why david might refer to the' b'messiah as his superior. we need only look at the scriptures' b'about the messiah to see that he is expected to be a great king,' b"bringing the jews to times even better than those under david's" b'rule. of course, the jews listening had no good answer, and the' b'passage could indeed refer to a divine messiah, such as the' b'christians worship. the problem lies in the meaning of this' b"psalm, an error that apparently several jews of jesus's time had" b'also made. one must remember that there were various factions' b'among the jews, often as a result of different expectations of the' b'messiah-king. jesus was apparently one of these adventists, like' b"his audience, who thought the messiah's advent was imminent, and" b'who interpreted psalms among others, as being messianic.' b'what is the problem, then? psalm literally reads,' b'' b"yhvh's utterance to my lord:" b'"sit at my right hand, until i make your enemies your' b'footstool."' b'' b'yhvh sends forth your mighty scepter from zion. rule' b'in the midst of your foes! your people will offer' b'themselves freely on the day you lead your host on the' b'holy mountains.' b'' b'"you are a priest of the order of melchizedek' b'forever."' b'' b'the word "lord" is often mistakenly capitalised by christian' b'bibles to denote divinity in this lord. but, in the hebrew, the' b'word is "adoni," and no capitalisation exists. adoni simply means' b'"lord," a generic term as we would use it. it is used often in' b"the scriptures to refer to kings and to g'd. it is merely an" b'address of respect.' b'there is nothing in the text itself to imply that the word' b'refers either to divinity or to the messiah-king. that this is' b'supposed to be written by david is not certain. the title of the' b'psalm translates to either "a psalm of david," or "a psalm about' b'david." it seems fitting to assume it to be written by a court' b"poet, about david's covenant and endorsement from g'd. if the" b'psalm had been written by david, it is unlikely that he would be' b'talking about the messiah. the idea of a perfect king, descended' b"from david, was not present in david's age. we have extensive" b"tales of david's doings and sayings-- none of which include any" b'praises of a messiah.' b'many of the psalms show evidence of being written long after' b"david was dead, in times of the exile when g'd had put his show of" b"favour for david's kingdom on hold." b'the description in the psalm fit david very well. david was' b"promised by g'd a rise to power, victory over his enemies," b'successful judgement among the nations he conquered. he achieved' b'the priesthood common to melchizedek in being a righteous king,' b'enabled to bless the people. it all fits.' b'we do not have to blame this problem on matthew alone,' b'though. here, there is not artificial prophecy alluded to, though' b'his use of the scripture is rather questionable. still, this' b'event is common to the other gospels too. so, we let matthew off' b'a little more easily this time. it is interesting to note,' b'though, how matthew dresses up the event. the earlier gospel of' b'mark tells the tale with jesus simply speaking to a crowd.' b'matthew has the pharisees, who became the religious competition of' b"an infant christianity, be the target of jesus's question. as we" b'might expect, matthew writes that the event ends up by' b'embarrassing the pharisees. such power is the pen.' b'' b'moses jesus,' b'had it together' b'all along...:' b'' b'we leave the gospel story of matthew momentarily to see a' b"pseudo-prophecy in john's gospel. the gospel story of john" b'deserves special treatment, because it seems to be so far removed' b"from the real events of jesus's career as told by even matthew." b'but, for the moment, we will just look at one verse. the early' b'church leaders founded a religion on the jewish hopes of a messiah' b'king, and on an artificial extension of the original promises made' b"by g'd. when constructing the history of abraham, moses wrote of" b'a promise of land and nationhood to t