' b'but, unfortunately, jesus made himself to explicit. he told his' b'disciples that their generation would still be around at the end,' b'and that they in particular should prepare for it, prepare to be' b'swept away.' b'there have been some who resorted to removing the inerrant' b'nature of the bible, and said that the phrase, "this generation' b'shall not pass away..." really means "this race of people will not' b'pass away..." of course, the word for generation is used many' b'times to refer to exactly that, the generation of the disciples.' b'it is an interesting notion that when god decided to learn greek,' b"he didn't learn it well enough to make himself clear. but. it is" b'quite obvious from the rest of the dialogue that the disciples (at' b'least some of them) are supposed to live to the end of the world.' b'the charge of mistranslation is completely blown away by looking' b"at the apostles' responses. it becomes abundantly clear from" b'rev. peter john and rev. that jesus' b'meant exactly what he said. the end was very near.' b'' b'for years, christians have rationalised this 24th' b'chapter of matthew, or ignored its meaning altogether. for b'years, they have waited for their executed leader to come back,' b'hearing of wars, and rumours of wars, sure that he is coming soon.' b'surely he must be. all we must do is wait. can you imagine how' b'tired he must be, sitting around up there, being holy, waiting for' b'just the right moment to spring?' b'' b'' b'so, shortly after his crucifixion, jesus of nazareth,' b'(joshua-ben-joseph), died. it is said that after three days, or' b'three days and three nights, or three periods of time, or three' b'eternal seconds --or three of whatever they can decide makes for' b'less trouble-- he was seen again, resurrected, glowing with divine' b"radiance. then the saviour decided it wasn't in the best" b'interests of his new religion to stick around, and therefore' b'disappeared from sight into heaven. so the story goes, anyway.' b'as has been seen, there were many things attributed to jesus when' b'people got around to writing the gospel stories down. to them,' b'jesus was the fulfiller of all prophecy and scripture. we have' b'seen, though, that this matter is quite shaky. but, throughout' b'church history, christians have held fast to faith, in simple' b'belief. what doctrinal objections could not be solved with' b'argumentation or brute force, faith and forgetfulness kept away' b'from question. to question and investigate has never been the' b'easiest way to treat matters. thus for years, the' b'prophecies cited in the new testament have gone on largely' b'accepted. things may well continue that way for some time.' b'pausing a moment to consider the way the doctrines of christianity' b'have been accepted and used (properly or improperly) to support' b'wars and persecution, i suppose there is one prophecy of which' b'christianity can securely keep hold.' b'' b'[mt jesus: "don\'t think that i have come to' b"bring peace on earth. i haven't come to bring peace," b'but rather a sword."' b'' b'' b'' 